2.2 Clean the data

Are there any redundant columns and rows? Are all the variables in the correct format (e.g., numeric, factor, date)? Lets fix it.

The variable loan_status contains information as to whether the loan has been repaid or charged off (i.e., defaulted). Lets create a binary factor variable for this. This variable will be the focus of this workshop.

lc_clean<- lc_raw %>%
  select(-where(~ mean(is.na(.)) > 0.9)) %>% # drop columns with more than 90% missing data
  filter(!is.na(int_rate)) %>%   #delete empty rows
  mutate(
    issue_d = mdy(issue_d),  # lubridate::mdy() to fix date format
    term = factor(term_months),     # turn 'term' into a categorical variable
    delinq_2yrs = factor(delinq_2yrs) # turn 'delinq_2yrs' into a categorical variable
  ) %>% 
  mutate(default = dplyr::recode(loan_status, 
                      "Charged Off" = "1", 
                      "Fully Paid" = "0"))%>%
    mutate(default = as.factor(default)) %>%
  dplyr::select(-emp_title,-installment, -term_months, everything()) #move some not-so-important variables to the end.

3 Linear vs.logistic regression for binary response variables (Q2)

It is certainly possible to use the OLS approach to find the line that minimizes the sum of squared errors when the dependent variable is binary (i.e., default / no default). In this case, the predicted values take the interpretation of a probability. We can also estimate a logistic regression instead. We do both below.

model_lm<-lm(as.numeric(default)~I(annual_inc/1000), lc_clean)
summary(model_lm)

Q2. Which model is more suitable for predicting probability of default, the linear regression or the logistic? Why?

Answer here: Logistic regression turns out to be more suitable in the prediction of probability because it constrains the prediction within 0 and 1, making the prediction interpretable as probabilities. Moreover, it models the relationship in a nonlinear way, capturing better the nature of binary outcomes.

4 Multivariate logistic regression (Q3, Q4)

We can estimate logistic regression with multiple explanatory variables as well. Lets use annual_inc, term, grade, and loan_amnt as features. Lets call this model logistic2.

logistic2 <- glm(default ~ annual_inc + term + grade + loan_amnt, family = "binomial", data = lc_clean)
summary(logistic2)

#compare the fit of logistic 1 & logistic 2
anova(logistic1,logistic2, test = "Chisq")

Q3. Based on logistic 2, explain the following:
a. Explain briefly the logic of MLE (maximum likelihood estimation).
b. What does the standard error of a coefficient mean?
c.What does the p-value of a coefficient mean?
d.What does deviance mean?
e. What does AIC mean?
f.What does null deviance mean?
g. Is Logistic 2 a better model than logistic 1? Why or why not?

Answer here: a. Maximum likelihood estimation estimates the model parameters by finding the values that maximize the likelihood of observing the given data. For logistic regression, MLE seeks the coefficients that maximize the probability of correctly predicting the observed binary outcomes. b. The standard error of a coefficient measures the precision of the coefficient estimate. A smaller standard error indicates that the estimate is more precise, whereas a larger standard error suggests greater uncertainty in the estimate. c.The p-value assesses whether the coefficient is significantly different from zero. A low p-value (typically < 0.05) indicates that the variable has a statistically significant impact on the outcome, suggesting that it likely contributes to predicting the probability of default. d.Deviance measures the models fit to the data; it quantifies the discrepancy between the observed outcomes and the models predictions. Lower deviance indicates a better fit to the data. e. AIC (Akaike Information Criterion) is a metric used for model selection that balances goodness of fit with model complexity. Lower AIC values indicate a better model by favoring models with fewer parameters while achieving a good fit. f.Null deviance represents the deviance of a model that includes only the intercept, providing a baseline measure of how well a no predictor model fits the data. g. Yes, Logistic 2 is a better model than Logistic 1, as indicated by the ANOVA test with test = Chisq, which shows a significant reduction in deviance (p < 2.2e-16). This implies that adding more variables (e.g.annual income, term, grade, loan amount) meaningfully improves the models fit to the data.

4.1 From probability to classification (Q5-Q10)

The logistic regression model gives us a sense of how likely defaults are; it gives us a probability estimate. To convert this into a prediction, we need to choose a cutoff probability and classify every loan with a predicted probability of default above the cutoff as a prediction of default (and vice versa for loans with a predicted probability below this cutoff).

Lets choose a threshold of 16%. Of course some of our predictions will turn out to be right but some will turn out to be wrong you can see this in the density figures of the previous section. Lets call default the positive class since this is the class we are trying to predict. We could be making two types of mistakes. False positives (i.e., predict that a loan will default when it will not) and false negatives (i.e., predict that a loan will not default when it does). These errors are summarized in the confusion matrix.

Q5. Produce the confusion matrix for the model logistic 2 for a cutoff of 16%

Insert your code here:

#using the logistic2 model predict default probabilities
prob_default2 <- predict(logistic2, type = "response")
  
#classify based onb 16% cutoff
p_class <- ifelse(prob_default2 > 0.16, "1", "0")
p_class <- factor(p_class, levels = levels(lc_clean$default))
  
#produce the confusion matrix
con2 <- caret::confusionMatrix(p_class, lc_clean$default, positive = "1")
con2

Q6. Using the confusion matrix, explain the following and show how they are calculated a.1. Accuracy a.2. Sensitivity a.3. Specificity For each of this explain what they mean in the context of the lending club and the goal of predicting loan defaults.

b. Moreover, compare each of these three statistics with the two extreme models: the models that predict that every instance is no default/default.

Answer here:

Termination: TP = true positive, TN = true negative, FP = false positive, FN = false negative, TP+TN+FP+FN = TPred.

a.1. the accuracy formula is = (TP+TN)/(TPred). (TP+TN) = 3225 + 21603 = 24828. Here (TPred) = 3225 + 21603 + 10837 + 2204 = 37869. So we have 24828/37869 = approx 0.6556. the accuracy represents the proportion of correct predictions for both defaults and non-defaults (grouped) i.e.in the case on the lending club, it indicates that 65.56% of the time, the model correctly classifies a loan in either default or non-default.

a.2. sensitivity is the proportion of actual defaults that the model correctly identifies, and its formula is = TP/(TP+FN). Here, TP = 3225 ; TP+FN = 3225 + 2204 = 5429 ; TP/(TP+FN) = 3225/5429 = approx 0.5940. This means that here, the model identifies approx 59.4% of loans that truly default. in the context ofd the lending club, it is essential to have a high sensitivity as it indicates that few defaults are missed by the model and can avoid lenders risky investments.

a.3. specificity is the proportion of actual non-defaults that thge model correctly identifies and its formula is = TN/(TN+FP). Here, TN = 21603 ; TN+FP = 21603 + 10837 = 32440 ; TN/(TN+FP) = 21603/32440 = approx 0.6659. This means that here, the model identifies approx 66.59% of loans that do not default. in the context of the lenfing club, a high specificity % reduces false positives i.e.it avoids wrongfully identifying safe loans as risky.

  1. Model predicting all no default:
  • Accuracy: according to the statistics in the confusion matrix, 85.66% of loans are non-defaults, therefore this model would have an accuracy of 85.66%.
  • Sensitivity: it would be 0% because it always predicts no defaults, thereby failing to identify defaults.
  • Specificity: 100% because it correctly identifies all non-defaults. The all no default model is risky for the lending club because although it avoids false positives (which is good), it fails to identify actual defaults. Model predicting all default:
  • Accuracy: this model would have an accuracy of 14.34% as only this proportion of loans actually default (100-85.66).
  • Sensitivity: 100% as it correctly identifies all defaults.
  • Specificity: 0% as it only identifies defaults and not non-defaults at all. The all default model increases the number of false positives as although it identifies every defauult, it classifies non-defaults as risky.

Before we look for a better model than logistic 2 lets see how we can use this model to select loans to invest. Lets make the simplistic assumption that every loan generates $15 profit if it is paid off and $75 loss if it is charged off for an investor. Lets use a cut-off value to determine which loans to invest in, that is, if the predicted probability of default for a loan is below this value then we invest in that loan and not if it is above.

To do this we split the data in three parts: training, validation, and testing. Feel free to experiment with different seeds but please use the seeds provided below for your submission.

Q11. Train logistic 2 on the training set above. Use the trained model to determine the optimal cut-off threshold based on the validation test. What is the optimal cutoff threshold? How much profit does it generate? Using the testing set, what is the profit per loan associated with the cutoff?

Insert your code here:

#estimating the model on the training set
logistic2 <- glm(default ~ annual_inc + term + grade + loan_amnt, family = "binomial", data = training)

#generating predicted probabilities of default for the validation set (val) 
p_val <- predict(logistic2, newdata = validation, type = "response")

unit_profit = 15
unit_loss = 75

#profit calculation function
profit_calculation <- function(cutoff) {
  predictions <- ifelse(p_val < cutoff, "0", "1")
  actual <- as.numeric(as.character(validation$default)) 
  
  #calculating profit based on actual vs predicted outcome
  profit <- ifelse(predictions == "0" & actual == "0", unit_profit, 
                   ifelse(predictions == "0" & actual == "1", -unit_loss, 0))
  sum(profit)
}

#finding the optimal cutoff that maximizes profit
cutoffs <- seq(0, 0.5, by = 0.01)
profits <- sapply(cutoffs, profit_calculation)
optimal_cutoff <- cutoffs[which.max(profits)]
max_profit <- max(profits)

#predicting probabilities on the testing set
p_test <- predict(logistic2, newdata = testing, type = "response")

#classification based on optimal cutoff
predictions_test <- ifelse(p_test < optimal_cutoff, "0", "1")
actual_test <- as.numeric(as.character(testing$default))

#calculating profit on the testing set
profit_test <- ifelse(predictions_test == "0" & actual_test == "0", unit_profit, 
                      ifelse(predictions_test == "0" & actual_test == "1", -unit_loss, 0))

#calculating average profit per loan on the testing set
avg_profit_per_loan <- mean(profit_test)


#display the optimal cutoff, max profit, and average profit per loan
optimal_cutoff
max_profit
avg_profit_per_loan

Insert your comments here: The code trains a logistic RM to predict loan defaults and defines a function to calculate total profit based on different probability cutoffs. By testing various cutoff values, it identifies 0.16 as the optimal cutoff, yielding a maximum profit of 31035 on the validation set. Using this cutoff on the testing set, the model achieves an average profit per loan of $4.39, ie the model is effective on unseen data.

5 More realistic revenue model (Q12-Q18)

Lets build a more realistic profit and loss model. Each loan has different terms (e.g., different interest rate and different duration) and therefore a different return if fully paid. For example, a 36 month loan of $5000 with instalment of $163 per month would generate a return of 163*36/5000-1=17.36% if there was no default. Lets assume that it would generate a loss of -60% if there was a default (the loss is not 100% because the loan may not default immediately and/or the lending club may be able to recover part of the loan).

Q13. Take the exact same setting as in Q10; however, assume that each time there is default we further incur a fixed cost of $ \(C\) in addition to the 60% loss. What is the maximum amount of \(C\) which would still give a positive mean return in the previous setting (i.e., investing $ 1 in each loan).

Insert your code here:

#define a function to compute the mean profit (+fixed cost per defaulted loan)
compute_mean_profit <- function(C) {
  updated_validation <- validation %>%
    mutate(
      #calculate profit margin: 60% loss plus fixed cost C for defaulted loans
      profit_margin = ifelse(default == "0", (installment * term_months / loan_amnt) - 1, -0.6 - C)) # 60% loss + fixed cost C for defaults
  
  mean(updated_validation$profit_margin) #calculate the mean profit
}

C_range <- seq(0, 1, by = 0.01) #range from 0 to 1 with 0.01 increments
profit_margins <- sapply(C_range, compute_mean_profit) #calculating mean profit for each

#finding the highest C that yields a positive mean profit
optimal_C <- max(C_range[profit_margins > 0])
optimal_C

Insert comments here:

From here onward, drop the assumption of an additional fixed cost as introduced in Q11 and take the revenue model introduced in Q10. Unfortunately, we cannot use the realized return to select loans to invest (as at the time we make the investment decision we do not know which loan will default). Instead, we can calculate an expected return using the estimated probabilities of default expected return = return if not default * (1-prob(default)) + return if default * prob(default).

Q14. Calculate the expected return of the loans in the validation set using the logistic2 model trained in the training set. Can you use the expected return metric to select a portfolio of the \(n\) most promising loans to invest in (\(n\) is an integer number)? How does the realized return vary as you change \(n\)? Insert your code here:

#convert "installment" & "term_months" to numeric data type in validation
validation <- validation %>%
  mutate(
    monthly_payment = as.numeric(installment),
    loan_term = as.numeric(term_months)
  )

#calculate projected return for each loan in validation
validation <- validation %>%
  mutate(default_probability = p_val,
    projected_return = (monthly_payment * loan_term / loan_amnt - 1) * (1 - default_probability) + (-0.6) * default_probability)

#sort loans by projected return in desc order for investment selection
ordered_loans <- validation %>% arrange(desc(projected_return))

#define different portfolio sizes
portfolio_sizes <- seq(100, 1000, by = 100) 

#create a vector to store realized returns for each portfolio size
portfolio_returns <- numeric(length(portfolio_sizes))

#iterate over each portfolio size, calculate & store the realized return
for (idx in seq_along(portfolio_sizes)) {
  portfolio_size <- portfolio_sizes[idx]
  
  #select the top loans based on projected return (for the current portfolio size)
  selected_portfolio <- ordered_loans[1:portfolio_size, ]
  
  #compute the actual return for the selected loans
  portfolio_returns[idx] <- mean(ifelse(selected_portfolio$default == "0", selected_portfolio$monthly_payment * selected_portfolio$loan_term / selected_portfolio$loan_amnt - 1, -0.6))
}

#calculate the actual profit for a portfolio size of 700 loans
target_portfolio_size <- 700
selected_700 <- ordered_loans[1:target_portfolio_size, ]

profit_for_700 <- mean(ifelse(selected_700$default == "0",
                              selected_700$monthly_payment * selected_700$loan_term / selected_700$loan_amnt - 1, 
                              -0.6))

#output results
list(Portfolio_Returns = portfolio_returns,
  Profit_for_700_Loans = profit_for_700)

Insert your comments: After computing the realized returns for different portfolio sizes, I noticed that smaller portfolios of top loans yield higher average returns, while the returns gradually decline as I include more loans. At a high level, what we have done in this assignment is a two-step process: (1) building a prediction model for loan defaults and (2) making decisions on which loans to invest in.

When we build our prediction model, our goal is to make accurate predictions on testing data (accuracy, sensitivity, specificity, AUC, AIC, etc.). When we make our investment decisions, our goal is to maximize profit (in our case, the average return of the selected loans in the testing data). Some loans offer higher returns than others. Are they equally important when we make our investment decisions? One argument is that we should care more about our prediction performance on high-return loans because we want to invest in non-defaulting, high-return loans.
